Scientific Question: Do the genes and proteins that are used for the UV-repair pathway in humans (specifically in nucleotide excision repair) have a high correlation in terms of gene similarity and protein structure with each other?¶

Background Information: There are two main categories of nucleotide excision repair: global genome nucleotide excision repair (GG-NER), and transcription-coupled nucleotide excision repair (TC-NER). The genes responsible for the processes wildly vary however.

Data: I found the genes and proteins responsible for NER on a separate website (https://www.mdanderson.org/documents/Labs/Wood-Laboratory/human-dna-repair-genes.html). I used NCBI and PDB to find the genes of interest. I found the genes and proteins responsible for NER on a separate website. I downloaded the files necessary through NCBI and PDB however. I used the genes ERCC2,ERCC3,XPC,XPA,and LIG1 as my genes/proteins of interest. They all have different functions except for XPC and XPA which both bind DNA.

Hypothesis: If the proteins, and thus genes, responsible for nucleotide excision repair each have completely different functions and structures, then the proteins and the genes responsible for them in nucleotide excision repair will not have a high sequence homology or structural homology in relation to each other.¶

Part 2: Pairwise Sequence Alignment¶

Pairwise sequence alignment compares the individual nucleotides in the different genes with each other You gets a pairwise alignment score that shows how many nucleotides matched.

In [12]:
#Reads in the fasta file using SeqIO, Fasta is a global variable
Fasta = list(SeqIO.parse("DataFiles.fasta", "fasta"))
#Sets global variable size to the length of Fasta
size = len(Fasta)
#code check
#print(size)
#creates empty array of size,size as the global variable alignments_score  
alignments_score = np.empty(shape=(size,size))

#Nested for loop to do pairwise sequence alignment for each pair of kinases
def pairwise_seq_heatmap(my_numpy_array, size):
    # loops over the kinases 
    for i in range(size):
        #loops over the kinases again
        for j in range(size):
        # x,y are local variables that define two sequences to be aligned. 
            X = Fasta[i].seq
            Y = Fasta[j].seq
            # Code Check below
            #print(Fasta[i].id)

        # Get a list of the global alignments between the two sequences ACGGGT and ACG
        # No parameters. Identical characters have score of 1, else 0.
        # No gap penalties.
        #my_numpy_array is a new created array that contains the global alignment scores
        #that is a local variable
            my_numpy_array[i,j] = int(pairwise2.align.globalxx(X, Y, score_only=True))
#returns array
    return my_numpy_array
#sets a new array with the pairwise sequence alignments as a global variable 
My_alignment_Scores = pairwise_seq_heatmap(alignments_score, size)
#code check
print(My_alignment_Scores)

Part 3: Heat map¶

A heat map is used to compare the similarities of the proteins/RNA through color visualization. A color bar will be added to show the degree of correlations of the proteins. This plot was used to visually analyze the alignment scores with each other. A higher or brighter color will mean that the two genes had more nucleotide homology.

#sets PDBParser function as p to simplify
p = PDBParser()
#creates global variables of the different proteins
structureXPA = p.get_structure("XPA", "XPA.pdb")
structureXPC = p.get_structure("XPC", "XPC.pdb")
structureERCC3 = p.get_structure("ERCC3", "ERCC3.pdb")

#These lines are commented out because their lines are discontinuous which makes them unable to be loaded in
#structureERCC2 = p.get_structure("ERCC2", "ERCC2.pdb")
#structureLIG1 = p.get_structure("LIG1", "LIG1.pdb")
#creates global variables of the two atoms that are furthest apart
XPA1=structureXPA[0]["A"][210]["CA"]
XPA2=structureXPA[0]["A"][98]["CA"]
XPC1=structureXPC[0]["A"][267]["CA"]
XPC2=structureXPC[0]["A"][288]["CA"]
ERCC3_1=structureERCC3[0]["A"][652]["CA"]
ERCC3_2=structureERCC3[0]["A"][524]["CA"]
#creates function distancefinder to find max distance
def distancefinder(atom1, atom2):
    #creates local variable distance
    distance=atom2-atom1
    return distance
#prints max distances of the different Proteins
print(distancefinder(XPA1,XPA2))
print(distancefinder(XPC1,XPC2))
print(distancefinder(ERCC3_1,ERCC3_2))

Analyzing results¶

The heatmap successfully shows the pairwise sequence alignment comparisons between the different nucleotide sequences. 0 is XPA, 1 is XPC, 2 is ERCC2, 3 is ERCC3, 4 is LIG1. The heatmap shows no definite correlation between two or more nucleotide sequences. The diagonals are the brightest because it compares the sequences to itself. XPA has around 35 thousand nucleotides. XPC has aroud 32 thousand nucleotides. ERCC3 has around 30 thousand nucleotides. ERCC2 has around 20 thousand nucleotides. LIG1 has around 22.5 thousand nucleotides. All of the sequence pairings relatively reflect their size of nucleotides as a higher number of nucleotides should always have a higher pairing as well just due to the amount. For instance, number3, or ERCC2 has the lowest number of nucleotides and that consequently has the lowest alignment score compared to others(as it has darker colors reflecting that). This suggests that my hypothesis is correct in taht there are no two or more genes that have a higher correlation or sequence homology with each other because each sequence have a relatively similar similarity percentage. The distancefinder function shows that the three proteins that were able to load in were relatively similar (in their 30s to 50s). This is probably due to the fact that enzymes are relatively similar in size if they have similar amounts of amino acids. This does however show that their curlings are relatively similar, and that one individual protein does not not fold multiple times. The PyMOL imaging which compares them together does show a significant increase in size for ERCC2 and LIG1, but those could not load in. If there would be one clumping of size then it would be those two (ERCC2 and LIG1), and the other three(ERCC3, XPA, and XPC). My hypothesis is correct in that the nucleotide sequence are not similar to one another. From the eye test however, XPA and XPC do look relatively similar in terms of their shape and size. Their max distance also reflects a similar grouping. Both their functions are to bind DNA so that may be why.
